    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nThe expected file type for `.mli` files is `ocaml_interface`, but when one is opened, the file type is set to `ocaml` which results in broken syntax highlighting (see below).\r\n\r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/64728420/9e45c762-e8f6-4579-9491-01debda57bbf)\r\n\r\nManually doing a `:se ft=ocaml_interface` fixes it.\r\n\r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/64728420/a603c3e2-e272-40c7-a08e-209d0ad55865)\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nOpen any `.mli` file.\r\n\r\n```vim\r\nset filetype?\r\n```\r\n\r\nwill say `ocaml`.\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nDoing\r\n\r\n```vim\r\nset filetype?\r\n```\r\n\r\non a(n) `.mli` file should output `ocaml_interface`.\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\n0.9.1\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nYes, but in case of Vim, the syntax highlighting is fine, even with the file type set to `ocaml`, in fact, setting it to `ocaml_interface` breaks, which works in Neovim. \r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nmacOS 14.0\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\niTerm2\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-256color\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nhomebrew",
    "closed_at": "2023-08-17T21:25:12Z",
